The best approach is to use the **`System.IO.Abstractions`** NuGet package — it's a battle-tested library that wraps the entire `System.IO` surface behind injectable interfaces.

## Setup

**1. Install the package:**
```bash
dotnet add package System.IO.Abstractions
```

**2. Register in DI:**
```csharp
builder.Services.AddSingleton<IFileSystem, FileSystem>();
```

**3. Inject `IFileSystem` into your classes:**
```csharp
public class ConfigManager(IFileSystem fileSystem)
{
    public string Load(string path)
        => fileSystem.File.ReadAllText(path);

    public void Save(string path, string content)
        => fileSystem.File.WriteAllText(path, content);

    public bool FolderExists(string path)
        => fileSystem.Directory.Exists(path);
}
```

## Testing

```bash
dotnet add <YourTestProject> package System.IO.Abstractions.TestingHelpers
```

```csharp
var mockFs = new MockFileSystem(new Dictionary<string, MockFileData>
{
    { "/data/config.json", new MockFileData("{\"key\": \"value\"}") }
});

var manager = new ConfigManager(mockFs);

Assert.Equal("{\"key\": \"value\"}", manager.Load("/data/config.json"));
Assert.True(manager.FolderExists("/data"));
```

## Why this over a custom wrapper?

| Custom wrapper | System.IO.Abstractions |
|---|---|
| You maintain it | Community-maintained, complete |
| Easy to miss edge cases | Covers streams, watchers, paths, etc. |
| Only wraps what you write | Drop-in replacement for all of `System.IO` |

The `MockFileSystem` gives you an in-memory filesystem that behaves like the real one — no temp files, no cleanup, and tests run in parallel safely.
